# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: use-after-free-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] A **code sanitizer** is a programming tool that detects bugs in the form of undefined or suspicious behavior by a compiler inserting instrumentation code at runtime.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] As of 2024, the most popular sanitizer is ASan, originally designed by Google.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] It is integrated into most mainstream compilers due to its relatively small memory and performance overhead.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Google's ASan, introduced in 2012, uses a shadow memory scheme to detect memory bugs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] The original design of the sanitizer increases processing time by about 73% and memory usage by 240%.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] There is a hardware-accelerated ASan called HWAsan available for AArch64 and (in a limited fashion) x86_64.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] AddressSanitizer does not detect any uninitialized memory reads (but this is detected by MemorySanitizer), and detects only some use-after-return bugs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] It is also not capable of detecting all arbitrary memory corruption bugs, nor all arbitrary write bugs due to integer underflow/overflows (when the integer with undefined behavior is used to calculate memory address offsets).
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Adjacent buffers in structs and classes are not protected from overflow, in part to prevent breaking backwards compatibility.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] The **KernelAddressSanitizer** (**KASan**) detects dynamic memory errors in the Linux kernel.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Kernel instrumentation requires a special feature in the compiler supplying the -fsanitize=kernel-address command line option, since kernels do not use the same address space as normal programs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] KASan is also available for use with Windows kernel drivers beginning in Windows 11 22H2 and above.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Similarly to Linux, compiling a Windows driver with KASAN requires passing the /fsanitize=kernel-address command line option to the MSVC compiler.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Google also produced **LeakSanitizer** (LSan, memory leaks), **ThreadSanitizer** (TSan, data races and deadlocks), **MemorySanitizer** (MSan, uninitialized memory), and **UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer** (**UBSan**, undefined behaviors, with fine-grained control).
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] These tools are generally available in Clang/LLVM and GCC.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Similar to KASan, there are kernel-specific versions of LSan, MSan, TSan, as well as completely original kernel sanitizers such as KFENCE and KCSan.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] A code sanitizer detects suspicious behavior as the program runs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] One common way to use a sanitizer is to combine it with fuzzing, which generates inputs likely to trigger bugs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] Chromium and Firefox developers are active users of AddressSanitizer; the tool has found hundreds of bugs in these web browsers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] A number of bugs were found in FFmpeg and FreeType.
[src:use-after-free-defense/addresssanitizer] The Linux kernel has enabled the AddressSanitizer for the x86-64 architecture as of Linux version 4.0.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The C++ programming language includes these functions; however, the operators new and delete provide similar functionality and are recommended by that language's authors.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Still, there are several situations in which using `new`/`delete` is not applicable, such as garbage collection code or performance-sensitive code, and a combination of `malloc` and `new` may be required instead of the higher-level `new` operator.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Many different implementations of the actual memory allocation mechanism, used by malloc, are available.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Their performance varies in both execution time and required memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The C programming language manages memory statically, automatically, or dynamically.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Static-duration variables are allocated in main memory, usually along with the executable code of the program, and persist for the lifetime of the program; automatic-duration variables are allocated on the stack and come and go as functions are called and return.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] For static-duration and automatic-duration variables, the size of the allocation must be compile-time constant (except for the case of variable-length automatic arrays).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] If the required size is not known until run-time (for example, if data of arbitrary size is being read from the user or from a disk file), then using fixed-size data objects is inadequate.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The lifetime of allocated memory can also cause concern.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Neither static- nor automatic-duration memory is adequate for all situations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Automatic-allocated data cannot persist across multiple function calls, while static data persists for the life of the program whether it is needed or not.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In many situations the programmer requires greater flexibility in managing the lifetime of allocated memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] These limitations are avoided by using dynamic memory allocation, in which memory is more explicitly (but more flexibly) managed, typically by allocating it from the heap (free storage), an area of memory structured for this purpose.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In C, the library function `malloc` is used to allocate a block of memory on the heap.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The program accesses this block of memory via a pointer that `malloc` returns.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] When the memory is no longer needed, the pointer is passed to `free` which deallocates the memory so that it can be used for other purposes.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The original description of C indicated that `calloc` and `cfree` were in the standard library, but not `malloc`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Code for a simple model implementation of a storage manager for Unix was given with `alloc` and `free` as the user interface functions, and using the `sbrk` system call to request memory from the operating system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The 6th Edition Unix documentation gives `alloc` and `free` as the low-level memory allocation functions.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The `malloc` and `free` routines in their modern form are completely described in the 7th Edition Unix manual.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Some platforms provide library or intrinsic function calls which allow run-time dynamic allocation from the C stack rather than the heap (e.g.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This memory is automatically freed when the calling function ends.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The C dynamic memory allocation functions are defined in `<stdlib.h>` header (`<cstdlib>` header in C++).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] However, the size of the array is fixed at compile time.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This computes the number of bytes that ten integers occupy in memory, then requests that many bytes from `malloc` and assigns the result to a pointer named `a` (due to C syntax, pointers and arrays can be used interchangeably in some situations).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The memory set aside by `malloc` is not initialized and may contain cruft: the remnants of previously used and discarded data.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] After allocation with `malloc`, elements of the array are uninitialized variables.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] With realloc we can resize the amount of memory a pointer points to.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] For example, if we have a pointer acting as an array of size n and we want to change it to an array of size m , we can use realloc.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Note that realloc must be assumed to have changed the base address of the block (i.e. if it has failed to extend the size of the original block, and has therefore allocated a new larger block elsewhere and copied the old contents into it).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Therefore, any pointers to addresses within the original block are also no longer valid.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] As stated earlier, `malloc` returns a void pointer (`void*`), which indicates that it is a pointer to a region of unknown data type.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The use of casting is required in C++ due to the strong type system, whereas this is not the case in C.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] There are advantages and disadvantages to performing such a cast.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Including the cast improves interoperability between C and C++, allowing C code to be compiled or used as C++.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Furthermore, the cast allows for pre-1989 versions of `malloc` that originally returned a `char*`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] However, under the C standard, the cast is not necessary, and adding the cast may mask failure to include the header `<stdlib.h>`, in which the function prototype for `malloc` is found.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In the absence of a prototype for `malloc`, the C90 standard requires that the C compiler assume `malloc` returns an `int`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] If there is no cast, C90 requires a diagnostic when this integer is assigned to the pointer; however, with the cast, this diagnostic would not be produced, hiding a bug.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Depending on calling conventions and memory layout, this may result in stack smashing.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This issue is less likely to go unnoticed in modern compilers, as C99 does not permit implicit declarations, so the compiler must produce a diagnostic even if it does assume `int` return.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Additionally, if the type of the pointer is changed at its declaration, the lines where `malloc` is called and the cast will have to be updated as well.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The improper use of dynamic memory allocation can frequently be a source of bugs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] These can include security bugs or program crashes, most often due to segmentation faults.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Memory allocation is not guaranteed to succeed, and may instead return a null pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This usually leads to crash (due to the resulting segmentation fault on the null pointer dereference), but there is no guarantee that a crash will happen so relying on that can also lead to problems.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] leads to the buildup of non-reusable memory, which is no longer used by the program.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This wastes memory resources and can lead to allocation failures when these resources are exhausted.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] twice ("double free"), etc., usually causes a segmentation fault and results in a crash of the program.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] These errors can be transient and hard to debug – for example, freed memory is usually not immediately reclaimed by the OS, and thus dangling pointers may persist for a while and appear to work.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In addition, as an interface that precedes ANSI C standardization, `malloc` and its associated functions have behaviors that were intentionally left to the implementation to define for themselves.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] One of them is the zero-length allocation, which is more of a problem with `realloc` since it is more common to resize to zero.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Although both POSIX and the Single Unix Specification require proper handling of 0-size allocations by either returning `NULL` or something else that can be safely freed, not all platforms are required to abide by these rules.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Among the many double-free errors that it has led to, the 2019 WhatsApp RCE was especially prominent.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] A way to wrap these functions to make them safer is by simply checking for 0-size allocations and turning them into those of size 1.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] (Returning `NULL` has its own problems: it otherwise indicates an out-of-memory failure.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The implementation of memory management depends greatly upon operating system and architecture.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Some operating systems supply an allocator for malloc, while others supply functions to control certain regions of data.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The same dynamic memory allocator is often used to implement both `malloc` and the operator `new` in C++.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Implementation of legacy allocators was commonly done using the heap segment.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The allocator would usually expand and contract the heap to fulfill allocation requests.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Doug Lea has developed the public domain dlmalloc ("Doug Lea's Malloc") as a general-purpose allocator, starting in 1987.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The GNU C library (glibc) is derived from Wolfram Gloger's ptmalloc ("pthreads malloc"), a fork of dlmalloc with threading-related improvements.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] As of November 2023, the latest version of dlmalloc is version 2.8.6 from August 2012.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In 2023 it was relicensed from CC0 to MIT-0.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Memory on the heap is allocated as "chunks", an 8-byte aligned data structure which contains a header, and usable memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Allocated memory contains an 8- or 16-byte overhead for the size of the chunk and usage flags (similar to a dope vector).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Unallocated chunks also store pointers to other free chunks in the usable space area, making the minimum chunk size 16 bytes on 32-bit systems and 24/32 (depends on alignment) bytes on 64-bit systems.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Unallocated memory is grouped into "bins" of similar sizes, implemented by using a double-linked list of chunks (with pointers stored in the unallocated space inside the chunk).
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Game developer Adrian Stone argues that `dlmalloc`, as a boundary-tag allocator, is unfriendly for console systems that have virtual memory but do not have demand paging.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This is because its pool-shrinking and growing callbacks (`sysmalloc`/`systrim`) cannot be used to allocate and commit individual pages of virtual memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In the absence of demand paging, fragmentation becomes a greater concern.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Since FreeBSD 7.0 and NetBSD 5.0, the old `malloc` implementation (`phkmalloc` by Poul-Henning Kamp) was replaced by jemalloc, written by Jason Evans.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The main reason for this was a lack of scalability of `phkmalloc` in terms of multithreading.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In order to avoid lock contention, `jemalloc` uses separate "arenas" for each CPU.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Experiments measuring number of allocations per second in multithreading application have shown that this makes it scale linearly with the number of threads, while for both phkmalloc and dlmalloc performance was inversely proportional to the number of threads.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] OpenBSD's implementation of the `malloc` function makes use of mmap.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] For requests greater in size than one page, the entire allocation is retrieved using `mmap`; smaller sizes are assigned from memory pools maintained by `malloc` within a number of "bucket pages", also allocated with `mmap`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] On a call to `free`, memory is released and unmapped from the process address space using `munmap`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The GrapheneOS project initially started out by porting OpenBSD's memory allocator to Android's Bionic C Library.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Hoard is an allocator whose goal is scalable memory allocation performance.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Like OpenBSD's allocator, Hoard uses `mmap` exclusively, but manages memory in chunks of 64 kilobytes called superblocks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Hoard's heap is logically divided into a single global heap and a number of per-processor heaps.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In addition, there is a thread-local cache that can hold a limited number of superblocks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] By allocating only from superblocks on the local per-thread or per-processor heap, and moving mostly-empty superblocks to the global heap so they can be reused by other processors, Hoard keeps fragmentation low while achieving near linear scalability with the number of threads.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] An open-source compact general-purpose memory allocator from Microsoft Research with focus on performance.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The library is about 11,000 lines of code.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Every thread has a thread-local storage for small allocations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] For large allocations mmap or sbrk can be used.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] TCMalloc, a *malloc* developed by Google, has garbage-collection for local storage of dead threads.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The TCMalloc is considered to be more than twice as fast as glibc's ptmalloc for multithreaded programs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Operating system kernels need to allocate memory just as application programs do.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The implementation of `malloc` within a kernel often differs significantly from the implementations used by C libraries, however.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] For example, memory buffers might need to conform to special restrictions imposed by DMA, or the memory allocation function might be called from interrupt context.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] This necessitates a `malloc` implementation tightly integrated with the virtual memory subsystem of the operating system kernel.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Because `malloc` and its relatives can have a strong impact on the performance of a program, it is not uncommon to override the functions for a specific application by custom implementations that are optimized for application's allocation patterns.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The C standard does not specify a way of doing this, but operating systems have found various ways to do this by exploiting dynamic linking.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] One way is to simply link in a different library to override the symbols.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Another, employed by Unix System V.3, is to make `malloc` and `free` function pointers that an application can reset to custom functions.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] which get defined in a header that all files that use memory allocation functions must include.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Theese macros should also replace the function `strdup`, since its result is passed to `free` too.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Data allocated inside of library functions (like `FILE` structures in the `stdio.h`) still get directly handled without using the wrappers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The most common form on POSIX-like systems is to set the environment variable LD_PRELOAD with the path of the allocator, so that the dynamic linker uses that version of malloc/calloc/free instead of the libc implementation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The largest possible memory block `malloc` can allocate depends on the host system, particularly the size of physical memory and the operating system implementation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Theoretically, the largest number should be the maximum value that can be held in a `size_t` type, which is an implementation-dependent unsigned integer representing the size of an area of memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] In the C99 standard and later, it is available as the `SIZE_MAX` constant from `<stdint.h>`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] Although not guaranteed by ISO C, it is usually `2^(CHAR_BIT * sizeof(size_t)) - 1`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] On glibc systems, the largest possible memory block `malloc` can allocate is only half this size, namely `2^(CHAR_BIT * sizeof(ptrdiff_t) - 1) - 1`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] On systems that use segmentation, like some memory models under MS-DOS, the largest possible memory block is typically one segment or less and thus significant smaller than the total address space, and `size_t` might be a smaller type than `ptrdiff_t`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/c-dynamic-memory-allocation] The C library implementations shipping with various operating systems and compilers may come with alternatives and extensions to the standard `malloc` interface.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Dangling pointers arise during object destruction, when an object that is pointed to by a given pointer is deleted or deallocated, without modifying the value of that said pointer, so that the pointer still points to the memory location of the deallocated memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] The system may reallocate the previously freed memory, and if the program then dereferences the (now) dangling pointer, *unpredictable behavior may result*, as the memory may now contain completely different data.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] If the program writes to memory referenced by a dangling pointer, a silent corruption of unrelated data may result, leading to subtle bugs that can be extremely difficult to find.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] If the memory has been reallocated to another process, then attempting to dereference the dangling pointer can cause segmentation faults (UNIX, Linux) or general protection faults (Windows).
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] If the program has sufficient privileges to allow it to overwrite the bookkeeping data used by the kernel's memory allocator, the corruption can cause system instabilities.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In object-oriented languages with garbage collection, dangling references are prevented by only destroying objects that are unreachable, meaning they do not have any incoming pointers; this is ensured either by tracing or reference counting.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] However, a finalizer may create new references to an object, requiring object resurrection to prevent a dangling reference.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers, also called uninitialized pointers, arise when a pointer is used prior to initialization to some known state, which is possible in some programming languages.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] They show the same erratic behavior as dangling pointers, though they are less likely to stay undetected because many compilers will raise a warning at compile time if declared variables are accessed before being initialized.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In many languages (e.g., the C programming language) deleting an object from memory explicitly or by destroying the stack frame on return does not alter associated pointers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] The pointer still points to the same location in memory even though that location may now be used for other purposes.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] If the operating system is able to detect run-time references to null pointers, a solution to the above is to assign 0 (null) to dp immediately before the inner block is exited.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Another solution would be to somehow guarantee dp is not used again without further initialization.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Another frequent source of dangling pointers is a jumbled combination of `malloc()` and `free()` library calls: a pointer becomes dangling when the block of memory it points to is freed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] As with the previous example one way to avoid this is to make sure to reset the pointer to null after freeing its reference—as demonstrated below.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] An all too common misstep is returning addresses of a stack-allocated local variable: once a called function returns, the space for these variables gets deallocated and technically they have "garbage values".
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Attempts to read from the pointer may still return the correct value (1234) for a while after calling `func`, but any functions called thereafter may overwrite the stack storage allocated for `num` with other values and the pointer would no longer work correctly.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] If a pointer to `num` must be returned, `num` must have scope beyond the function—it might be declared as `static`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Antoni Kreczmar (1945–1996) has created a complete object management system which is free of dangling reference phenomenon.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] A similar approach was proposed by Fisher and LeBlanc under the name *Locks-and-keys*.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers are created by omitting necessary initialization prior to first use.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Thus, strictly speaking, every pointer in programming languages which do not enforce initialization begins as a wild pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] This most often occurs due to jumping over the initialization, not by omitting it.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Most compilers are able to warn about this.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Like buffer-overflow bugs, dangling/wild pointer bugs frequently become security holes.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] For example, if the pointer is used to make a virtual function call, a different address (possibly pointing at exploit code) may be called due to the vtable pointer being overwritten.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Alternatively, if the pointer is used for writing to memory, some other data structure may be corrupted.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Even if the memory is only read once the pointer becomes dangling, it can lead to information leaks (if interesting data is put in the next structure allocated there) or to privilege escalation (if the now-invalid memory is used in security checks).
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] When a dangling pointer is used after it has been freed without allocating a new chunk of memory to it, this becomes known as a "use after free" vulnerability.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] For example, CVE-2014-1776 is a use-after-free vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer 6 through 11 that was used by zero-day attacks by an advanced persistent threat.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In C, the simplest technique is to implement an alternative version of the `free()` (or alike) function which guarantees the reset of the pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] However, this technique will not clear other pointer variables which may contain a copy of the pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] These uses can be masked through `#define` directives to construct useful macros (a common one being `#define XFREE(ptr) safeFree((void**)&(ptr))`), creating something like a metalanguage or can be embedded into a tool library apart.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In every case, programmers using this technique should use the safe versions in every instance where `free()` would be used; failing in doing so leads again to the problem.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Also, this solution is limited to the scope of a single program or project, and should be properly documented.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Among more structured solutions, a popular technique to avoid dangling pointers in C++ is to use smart pointers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] A smart pointer typically uses reference counting to reclaim objects.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Some other techniques include the tombstones method and the locks-and-keys method.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use the Boehm garbage collector, a conservative garbage collector that replaces standard memory allocation functions in C and C++ with a garbage collector.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] This approach completely eliminates dangling pointer errors by disabling frees, and reclaiming objects by garbage collection.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use a system such as CHERI, which stores pointers with additional metadata which may prevent invalid accesses by including lifetime information in pointers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] CHERI typically requires support in the CPU to conduct these additional checks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In languages like Java, dangling pointers cannot occur because there is no mechanism to explicitly deallocate memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Rather, the garbage collector may deallocate memory, but only when the object is no longer reachable from any references.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] In the language Rust, the type system has been extended to include also the variables lifetimes and resource acquisition is initialization.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Unless one disables the features of the language, dangling pointers will be caught at compile time and reported as programming errors.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] To expose dangling pointer errors, one common programming technique is to set pointers to the null pointer or to an invalid address once the storage they point to has been released.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] When the null pointer is dereferenced (in most languages) the program will immediately terminate—there is no potential for data corruption or unpredictable behavior.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] This makes the underlying programming mistake easier to find and resolve.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] This technique does not help when there are multiple copies of the pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Some debuggers will automatically overwrite and destroy data that has been freed, usually with a specific pattern, such as `0xDEADBEEF` (Microsoft's Visual C/C++ debugger, for example, uses `0xCC`, `0xCD` or `0xDD` depending on what has been freed).
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] This usually prevents the data from being reused by making it useless and also very prominent (the pattern serves to show the programmer that the memory has already been freed).
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Tools such as Polyspace, TotalView, Valgrind, Mudflap, AddressSanitizer, or tools based on LLVM can also be used to detect uses of dangling pointers.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] Other tools (SoftBound, Insure++, and CheckPointer) instrument the source code to collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity.
[src:use-after-free-defense/dangling-pointer] The ARM64 memory tagging extension (MTE) - disabled by default on Linux systems, but can be enabled on Android 16 - triggers a segmentation fault when it detects use-after-free and buffer overflow.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] In computer science, **manual memory management** refers to the usage of manual instructions by the programmer to identify and deallocate unused objects, or garbage.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Up until the mid-1990s, the majority of programming languages used in industry supported manual memory management, though garbage collection has existed since 1959, when it was introduced with Lisp.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Today, however, languages with garbage collection such as Java are increasingly popular and the languages Objective-C and Swift provide similar functionality through Automatic Reference Counting.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] The main manually managed languages still in widespread use today are C and C++ – see C dynamic memory allocation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Many programming languages use manual techniques to determine when to *allocate* a new object from the free store.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] C uses the `malloc` function; C++ and Java use the `new` operator; and many other languages (such as Python) allocate all objects from the free store.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Determining when an object ought to be created (object creation) is generally trivial and unproblematic, though techniques such as object pools mean an object may be created before immediate use.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] The real challenge is object destruction – determination of when an object is no longer needed (i.e. is garbage), and arranging for its underlying storage to be returned to the free store for re-use.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Manual memory management is known to enable several major classes of bugs into a program when used incorrectly, notably violations of memory safety or memory leaks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] These are a significant source of security bugs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Languages which exclusively use garbage collection are known to avoid the last two classes of defects.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Memory leaks can still occur (and bounded leaks frequently occur with generational or conservative garbage collection), but are generally less severe than memory leaks in manual systems.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Manual memory management has one correctness advantage, which is that it allows automatic resource management via the resource acquisition is initialization (RAII) paradigm.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This arises when objects own scarce system resources (like graphics resources, file handles, or database connections) which must be relinquished when an object is destroyed – when the lifetime of the resource ownership should be tied to the lifetime of the object.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Languages with manual management can arrange this by acquiring the resource during object initialization (in the constructor), and releasing during object destruction (in the destructor), which occurs at a precise time.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII).
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This can also be used with deterministic reference counting.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] In C++, this ability is put to further use to automate memory deallocation within an otherwise-manual framework, use of smart pointers in the language's standard library to perform memory management is a common paradigm.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] In languages like Rust which enforce strict ownership, RAII becomes the default behavior for managing resources.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This approach is not usable in most garbage collected languages – notably tracing garbage collectors or more advanced reference counting – due to finalization being non-deterministic, and sometimes not occurring at all.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] That is, it is difficult to define (or determine) when or if a finalizer method might be called; this is commonly known as the finalizer problem.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Programmers are expected to invoke `dispose()` manually as appropriate to prevent "leaking" of scarce graphics resources.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] A defer mechanism is a feature that allows the postponing of execution of a piece of code until later, usually either the end of scope or end of a function.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This can be seen as similar to a finally block in other languages.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] C (beginning in C29) introduces a `defer` mechanism.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Each `defer` block which is encountered in execution is run at scope exit (not when encountered), in the reverse order they were encountered.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] C++ has not yet commented on whether or not it will integrate C `defer`, as RAII covers this use case.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] In Go, `defer` is used to schedule a function call to run when the surrounding function returns.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Multiple `defer`s run in last-in-first-out (LIFO) order.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] In Zig, `defer` is block-level and runs when the current scope ends, not just the function.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Unlike Go, Zig `defer` incurs no overhead.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Zig also includes `errdefer`, which runs only if the function exits with an error.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Many advocates of manual memory management argue that it affords superior performance when compared to automatic techniques such as garbage collection.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Traditionally latency was the biggest advantage, but this is no longer the case.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation frequently has superior locality of reference.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation is also known to be more appropriate for systems where memory is a scarce resource, due to faster reclamation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Latency is a debated point that has changed over time, with early garbage collectors and simple implementations performing very poorly compared to manual memory management, but sophisticated modern garbage collectors often performing as well or better than manual memory management.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation does not suffer from the long "pause" times that occur in simple stop-the-world garbage collection, although modern garbage collectors have collection cycles which are often not noticeable.
[src:use-after-free-defense/manual-memory-management] This is especially an issue in real time systems, where unbounded collection cycles are generally unacceptable; real-time garbage collection is possible by pausing the garbage collector, while real-time manual memory management requires avoiding large deallocations, or manually pausing deallocation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] In computer science, a **memory leak** is a type of resource leak that occurs when a computer program incorrectly manages memory allocations in a way that memory which is no longer needed is not released.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A memory leak may also happen when an object is stored in memory but cannot be accessed by the running code (i.e. unreachable memory).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A memory leak has symptoms similar to a number of other problems and generally can only be diagnosed by a programmer with access to the program's source code.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A related concept is the "space leak", which is when a program consumes excessive memory but does eventually release it.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Because they can exhaust available system memory as an application runs, memory leaks are often the cause of or a contributing factor to software aging.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If a program has a memory leak and its memory usage is steadily increasing, there will not usually be an immediate symptom.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] In modern operating systems, normal memory used by an application is released when the application terminates.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] This means that a memory leak in a program that only runs for a short time may not be noticed and is rarely serious, and slow leaks can also be covered over by program restarts.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Every physical system has a finite amount of memory, and if the memory leak is not contained (for example, by restarting the leaking program) it will eventually cause problems for users.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Most modern consumer desktop operating systems have both main memory which is physically housed in RAM microchips, and secondary storage such as a hard drive.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Memory allocation is dynamic – each process gets as much memory as it requests.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Active pages are transferred into main memory for fast access; inactive pages are pushed out to secondary storage to make room, as needed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] When a single process starts consuming a large amount of memory, it usually occupies more and more of main memory, pushing other programs out to secondary storage – usually significantly slowing performance of the system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Even if the leaking program is terminated, it may take some time for other programs to swap back into main memory, and for performance to return to normal.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The resulting slowness and excessive accessing of secondary storage is known as thrashing.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If a program uses all available memory before being terminated (whether there is virtual memory or only main memory, such as on an embedded system) any attempt to allocate more memory will fail.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] This usually causes the program attempting to allocate the memory to terminate itself, or to generate a segmentation fault.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Some programs are designed to recover from this situation (possibly by falling back on pre-reserved memory).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The first program to experience the out-of-memory may or may not be the program that has the memory leak.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Some multi-tasking operating systems have special mechanisms to deal with an out-of-memory condition, such as killing processes at random (which may affect "innocent" processes), or killing the largest process in memory (which presumably is the one causing the problem).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Some operating systems have a per-process memory limit, to prevent any one program from hogging all of the memory on the system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The disadvantage to this arrangement is that the operating system sometimes must be re-configured to allow proper operation of programs that legitimately require large amounts of memory, such as those dealing with graphics, video, or scientific calculations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If the memory leak is in the kernel, the operating system itself will likely fail.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Computers without sophisticated memory management, such as embedded systems, may also completely fail from a persistent memory leak.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Memory leaks are a common error in programming, especially when using languages that have no built in automatic garbage collection, such as C and C++.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Typically, a memory leak occurs because dynamically allocated memory has become unreachable.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The prevalence of memory leak bugs has led to the development of a number of debugging tools to detect unreachable memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] *BoundsChecker*, *Deleaker*, Memory Validator, *IBM Rational Purify*, *Valgrind*, *Parasoft Insure++*, *Dr.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Memory* and *memwatch* are some of the more popular memory debuggers for C and C++ programs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] "Conservative" garbage collection capabilities can be added to any programming language that lacks it as a built-in feature, and libraries for doing this are available for C and C++ programs.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A conservative collector finds and reclaims most, but not all, unreachable memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Although the memory manager can recover unreachable memory, it cannot free memory that is still reachable and therefore potentially still useful.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Modern memory managers therefore provide techniques for programmers to semantically mark memory with varying levels of usefulness, which correspond to varying levels of *reachability*.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The memory manager does not free an object that is strongly reachable.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] An object is strongly reachable if it is reachable either directly by a strong reference or indirectly by a chain of strong references.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] In general, automatic memory management is more robust and convenient for developers, as they do not need to implement freeing routines or worry about the sequence in which cleanup is performed or be concerned about whether or not an object is still referenced.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] It is easier for a programmer to know when a reference is no longer needed than to know when an object is no longer referenced.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] However, automatic memory management can impose a performance overhead, and it does not eliminate all of the programming errors that cause memory leaks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Publicly accessible systems such as web servers or routers are prone to denial-of-service attacks if an attacker discovers a sequence of operations which can trigger a leak.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Resource acquisition is initialization (RAII) is an approach to the problem commonly taken in C++, D, and Ada.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] It involves associating scoped objects with the acquired resources, and automatically releasing the resources once the objects are out of scope.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Unlike garbage collection, RAII has the advantage of knowing when objects exist and when they do not.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The C version, as implemented in the example, requires explicit deallocation; the array is dynamically allocated (from the heap in most C implementations), and continues to exist until explicitly freed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The C++ version requires no explicit deallocation; it will always occur automatically as soon as the object `a` goes out of scope, including if an exception is thrown.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] This avoids some of the overhead of garbage collection schemes.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] And because object destructors can free resources other than memory, RAII helps to prevent the leaking of input and output resources accessed through a handle, which mark-and-sweep garbage collection does not handle gracefully.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] These include open files, open windows, user notifications, objects in a graphics drawing library, thread synchronisation primitives such as critical sections, network connections, and connections to the Windows Registry or another database.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] However, using RAII correctly is not always easy and has its own pitfalls.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] For instance, if one is not careful, it is possible to create dangling pointers (or references) by returning data by reference, only to have that data be deleted when its containing object goes out of scope.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] D uses a combination of RAII and garbage collection, employing automatic destruction when it is clear that an object cannot be accessed outside its original scope, and garbage collection otherwise.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] More modern garbage collection schemes are often based on a notion of reachability – if you do not have a usable reference to the memory in question, it can be collected.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Other garbage collection schemes can be based on reference counting, where an object is responsible for keeping track of how many references are pointing to it.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If the number goes down to zero, the object is expected to release itself and allow its memory to be reclaimed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The flaw with this model is that it does not cope with cyclic references, and this is why nowadays most programmers are prepared to accept the burden of the more costly mark and sweep type of systems.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] In practice, this trivial example would be spotted straight away and fixed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] In most real examples, the cycle of references spans more than two objects, and is more difficult to detect.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A well-known example of this kind of leak came to prominence with the rise of AJAX programming techniques in web browsers in the lapsed listener problem.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] JavaScript code which associated a DOM element with an event handler, and failed to remove the reference before exiting, would leak memory (AJAX web pages keep a given DOM alive for a lot longer than traditional web pages, so this leak was much more apparent).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] A "sawtooth" pattern of memory utilization may be an indicator of a memory leak within an application, particularly if the vertical drops coincide with reboots or restarts of that application.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Care should be taken though because garbage collection points could also cause such a pattern and would show a healthy usage of the heap.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Constantly increasing memory usage is not necessarily evidence of a memory leak.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Some applications will store ever increasing amounts of information in memory (e.g. as a cache).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If the cache can grow so large as to cause problems, this may be a programming or design error, but is not a memory leak as the information remains nominally in use.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Confirmation that excessive memory use is due to a memory leak requires access to the program code.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The following example, written in pseudocode, is intended to show how a memory leak can come about, and its effects, without needing any programming knowledge.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The program in this case is part of some very simple software designed to control an elevator.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] This part of the program is run whenever anyone inside the elevator presses the button for a floor.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The memory leak would occur if the floor number requested is the same floor that the elevator is on; the condition for releasing the memory would be skipped.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Each time this case occurs, more memory is leaked.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] Cases like this would not usually have any immediate effects.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] People do not often press the button for the floor they are already on, and in any case, the elevator might have enough spare memory that this could happen hundreds or thousands of times.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] However, the elevator will eventually run out of memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] This could take months or years, so it might not be discovered despite thorough testing.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The consequences would be unpleasant; at the very least, the elevator would stop responding to requests to move to another floor (such as when an attempt is made to call the elevator or when someone is inside and presses the floor buttons).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] If other parts of the program need memory (a part assigned to open and close the door, for example), then no one would be able to enter, and if someone happens to be inside, they will become trapped (assuming the doors cannot be opened manually).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The memory leak lasts until the system is reset.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] For example: if the elevator's power were turned off or in a power outage, the program would stop running.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] When power was turned on again, the program would restart and all the memory would be available again, but the slow process of memory leak would restart together with the program, eventually prejudicing the correct running of the system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-leak] The following C++ function deliberately leaks memory by losing the pointer to the allocated memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Several methods have been devised that increase the effectiveness of memory management.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Virtual memory systems separate the memory addresses used by a process from actual physical addresses, allowing separation of processes and increasing the size of the virtual address space beyond the available amount of RAM using paging or swapping to secondary storage.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The quality of the virtual memory manager can have an extensive effect on overall system performance.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The system allows a computer to appear as if it may have more memory available than physically present, thereby allowing multiple processes to share it.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Burroughs/Unisys MCP, and OS/360 and successors, memory is managed by the operating system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Unix-like operating systems, memory is managed at the application level.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory management within an address space is generally categorized as either manual memory management or automatic memory management.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The task of fulfilling an allocation request consists of locating a block of unused memory of sufficient size.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory requests are satisfied by allocating portions from a large pool of memory called the *heap* or *free store*.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] At any given time, some parts of the heap are in use, while some are "free" (unused) and thus available for future allocations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In the C language, the function which allocates memory from the heap is called `malloc` and the function which takes previously allocated memory and marks it as "free" (to be used by future allocations) is called `free`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Several issues complicate the implementation, such as external fragmentation, which arises when there are many small gaps between allocated memory blocks, which invalidates their use for an allocation request.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The allocator's metadata can also inflate the size of (individually) small allocations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory management system must track outstanding allocations to ensure that they do not overlap and that no memory is ever "lost" (i.e. that there are no "memory leaks").
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The specific dynamic memory allocation algorithm implemented can impact performance significantly.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A study conducted in 1994 by Digital Equipment Corporation illustrates the overheads involved for a variety of allocators.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The lowest average instruction path length required to allocate a single memory slot was 52 (as measured with an instruction level profiler on a variety of software).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Since the precise location of the allocation is not known in advance, the memory is accessed indirectly, usually through a pointer reference.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Fixed-size blocks allocation, also called memory pool allocation, uses a free list of fixed-size blocks of memory (often all of the same size).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This works well for simple embedded systems where no large objects need to be allocated but suffers from fragmentation especially with long memory addresses.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] However, due to the significantly reduced overhead, this method can substantially improve performance for objects that need frequent allocation and deallocation, and so it is often used in video games.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In this system, memory is allocated into several pools of memory instead of just one, where each pool represents blocks of memory of a certain power of two in size, or blocks of some other convenient size progression.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] All blocks of a particular size are kept in a sorted linked list or tree and all new blocks that are formed during allocation are added to their respective memory pools for later use.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] If a smaller size is requested than is available, the smallest available size is selected and split.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When a block is split, it is divided into two smaller blocks, and each smaller block becomes a unique "buddy" to the other.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] One of the resulting parts is selected, and the process repeats until the request is complete.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When a block is allocated, the allocator will start with the smallest sufficiently large block to avoid needlessly breaking blocks.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When a block is freed, it is compared to its buddy.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] If they are both free, they are combined and placed in the correspondingly larger-sized buddy-block list.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This memory allocation mechanism preallocates memory chunks suitable to fit objects of a certain type or size.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] These chunks are called caches and the allocator only has to keep track of a list of free cache slots.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Constructing an object will use any one of the free cache slots and destructing an object will add a slot back to the free cache slot list.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This technique alleviates memory fragmentation and is efficient as there is no need to search for a suitable portion of memory, as any open slot will suffice.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Many Unix-like systems as well as Microsoft Windows implement a function called `alloca` for dynamically allocating stack memory in a way similar to the heap-based `malloc`.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A compiler typically translates it to inlined instructions manipulating the stack pointer.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Although there is no need of manually freeing memory allocated this way, as it is automatically freed when the function that called `alloca` returns, there exists a risk of overflow.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] And since alloca is an *ad hoc* expansion seen in many systems but never in POSIX or the C standard, its behavior in case of a stack overflow is undefined.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A safer version of alloca called `_malloca`, which reports errors, exists on Microsoft Windows.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] It requires the use of `_freea`. gnulib provides an equivalent interface, albeit instead of throwing an SEH exception on overflow, it delegates to malloc when an overlarge size is detected.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A similar feature can be emulated using manual accounting and size-checking, such as in the uses of `alloca_account` in glibc.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The proper management of memory in an application is a difficult problem, and several different strategies for handling memory management have been devised.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Special declarations may allow local variables to retain values between invocations of the procedure, or may allow local variables to be accessed by other subroutines.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The automatic allocation of local variables makes recursion possible, to a depth limited by available memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Garbage collection is a strategy for automatically detecting memory allocated to objects that are no longer usable in a program, and returning that allocated memory to a pool of free memory locations.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This method is in contrast to "manual" memory management where a programmer explicitly codes memory requests and memory releases in the program.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] While automatic garbage collection has the advantages of reducing programmer workload and preventing certain kinds of memory allocation bugs, garbage collection does require memory resources of its own, and can compete with the application program for processor time.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Reference counting is a strategy for detecting that memory is no longer usable by a program by maintaining a counter for how many independent pointers point to the memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Whenever a new pointer points to a piece of memory, the programmer is supposed to increase the counter.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When the pointer changes where it points, or when the pointer is no longer pointing to any area or has itself been freed, the counter should decrease.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When the counter drops to zero, the memory should be considered unused and freed.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Some reference counting systems require programmer involvement and some are implemented automatically by the compiler.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A disadvantage of reference counting is that circular references can develop which cause a memory leak to occur.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This can be mitigated by either adding the concept of a "weak reference" (a reference that does not participate in reference counting, but is notified when the area it is pointing to is no longer valid) or by combining reference counting and garbage collection together.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] A memory pool is a technique of automatically deallocating memory based on the state of the application, such as the lifecycle of a request or transaction.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The idea is that many applications execute large chunks of code which may generate memory allocations, but that there is a point in execution where all of those chunks are known to be no longer valid.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] For example, in a web service, after each request the web service no longer needs any of the memory allocated during the execution of the request.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Therefore, rather than keeping track of whether or not memory is currently being referenced, the memory is allocated according to the request or lifecycle stage with which it is associated.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] When that request or stage has passed, all associated memory is deallocated simultaneously.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Virtual memory is a method of decoupling the memory organization from the physical hardware.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The applications operate on memory via *virtual addresses*.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Each attempt by the application to access a particular virtual memory address results in the virtual memory address being translated to an actual *physical address*.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In this way the addition of virtual memory enables granular control over memory systems and methods of access.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In virtual memory systems the operating system limits how a process can access the memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] This feature, called memory protection, can be used to disallow a process to read or write to memory that is not allocated to it, preventing malicious or malfunctioning code in one program from interfering with the operation of another.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Even though the memory allocated for specific processes is normally isolated, processes sometimes need to be able to share information.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Shared memory is one of the fastest techniques for inter-process communication.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory is usually classified by access rate into primary storage and secondary storage.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory management systems, among other operations, also handle the moving of information between these two levels of memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] An operating system manages various resources in the computing system.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory subsystem is the system element for managing memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory subsystem combines the hardware memory resource and the MCP OS software that manages the resource.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory subsystem manages the physical memory and the virtual memory of the system (both part of the hardware resource).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The virtual memory extends physical memory by using extra space on a peripheral device, usually disk.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for moving code and data between main and virtual memory in a process known as overlaying.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Burroughs was the first commercial implementation of virtual memory (although developed at Manchester University for the Ferranti Atlas computer) and integrated virtual memory with the system design of the B5000 from the start (in 1961) needing no external memory management unit (MMU).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The memory subsystem is responsible for mapping logical requests for memory blocks to physical portions of memory (segments) which are found in the list of free segments.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Descriptors are essential in providing memory safety and security so that operations cannot overflow or underflow the referenced block (commonly known as buffer overflow).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Descriptors themselves are protected control words that cannot be manipulated except for specific elements of the MCP OS (enabled by the UNSAFE block directive in NEWP).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Donald Knuth describes a similar system in Section 2.5 ‘Dynamic Storage Allocation’ of ‘Fundamental Algorithms’.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] IBM System/360 does not support virtual memory.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory isolation of jobs is optionally accomplished using protection keys, assigning storage for each job a different key, 0 for the supervisor or 1–15.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory management in OS/360 is a supervisor function.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Storage is requested using the `GETMAIN` macro and freed using the `FREEMAIN` macro, which result in a call to the supervisor (SVC) to perform the operation.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In OS/360 the details vary depending on how the system is generated, e.g., for PCP, MFT, MVT.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In OS/360 MVT, suballocation within a job's *region* or the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is based on *subpools*, areas a multiple of 2 KB in size—the size of an area protected by a protection key.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Within a region subpools are assigned either the job's storage protection or the supervisor's key, key 0.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Initially only subpool zero is created, and all user storage requests are satisfied from subpool 0, unless another is specified in the memory request.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Subpools 250–255 are created by memory requests by the supervisor on behalf of the job.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Most of these are assigned key 0, although a few get the key of the job.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Subpool numbers are also relevant in MFT, although the details are much simpler.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] MFT uses fixed *partitions* redefinable by the operator instead of dynamic regions and PCP has only a single partition.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Each subpool is mapped by a list of control blocks identifying allocated and free memory blocks within the subpool.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Memory is allocated by finding a free area of sufficient size, or by allocating additional blocks in the subpool, up to the region size of the job.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] It is possible to free all or part of an allocated memory area.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] The details for OS/VS1 are similar to those for MFT and for MVT; the details for OS/VS2 are similar to those for MVT, except that the page size is 4 KiB.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] For both OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 the shared *System Queue Area* (SQA) is nonpageable.
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] In MVS the address space includes an additional pageable shared area, the *Common Storage Area* (CSA), and two additional private areas, the nonpageable *local system queue area* (LSQA) and the pageable *System Work area* (SWA).
[src:use-after-free-defense/memory-management] Also, the storage keys 0–7 are all reserved for use by privileged code.
